Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
File mode constants exposed by the cross-platform dispatcher's bare-name API.
Linux ARM32 uses the same `mode_t` encoding as every other Linux architecture:
the low 9 bits are the rwxrwxrwx permission triplet, encoded octally as
0644 (rw-r--r--) and 0755 (rwxr-xr-x). The values below are the decimal
equivalents of those octal constants, as required by the syscall ABI which
treats the mode argument as a plain integer. Source: Linux kernel
`include/uapi/linux/stat.h` (S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200, S_IRGRP=0040,
S_IWGRP=0020, S_IROTH=0004, S_IWOTH=0002, S_IXUSR=0100, S_IXGRP=0010,
S_IXOTH=0001). 0644 = 0400|0200|0040|0004 = 420 decimal. 0755 =
0400|0200|0100|0040|0010|0004|0001 = 493 decimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value.
The dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` lookup resolves to this proc on
Linux ARM32 targets via the bare-name route established in Wave 1.
Wave 2 will rename to `linux_arm32_MODE_0644`; Wave 1 keeps the bare form
to match the still-bare dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
These accessors are constant returns; the compiler is expected to inline
them at every call site, leaving zero call overhead. Do not introduce any
runtime computation here.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file permission constant carries no security state. Callers
who use the returned value as a `mode` argument to `creat`/`open(O_CREAT)`/
`mkdir`/`chmod` are responsible for ensuring the requested permission
matches the intended access policy. World-readable (0644) is appropriate
for non-sensitive files; group-and-world-executable (0755) is appropriate
for binaries and directories.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "linux_arm32_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0644 octal = rw-r--r--
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x
End Process

