Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file, SEEK_CUR
(1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END (2) measures
relative to end-of-file. Linux ARM32 inherits the same values as every
Linux architecture, defined in `include/uapi/linux/fs.h` and the POSIX
specification. These match the bare-name dispatcher's expectations and
the `syscall_lseek` wrapper's `whence` parameter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from Syscall` to this proc on linux_arm32
targets via the bare-name pattern still in force during Wave 1. Bodies
are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its own.
Callers that pass user-influenced `offset` values into `lseek` with these
whence flags MUST validate the resulting absolute file position against
the file's permitted range; an attacker-controlled negative offset
combined with SEEK_END can yield an unexpected position prior to file
start, which `lseek` will reject with EINVAL on conforming Linux kernels.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "linux_arm32_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Seek from beginning of file
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Seek from current position
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Seek from end of file
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERIC SYSCALL WRAPPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Linux ARM32 syscall convention:
Note: - R7 = syscall number
Note: - R0-R6 = arguments 1-7
Note: - Return value in R0

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Linux ARM32 syscall with 0 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into R7
        ldr r7, [fp, #-4]

        # Execute syscall
        swi #0

        # Store result from R0
        str r0, [fp, #-8]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_1" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Linux ARM32 syscall with 1 argument
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into R7
        ldr r7, [fp, #-4]

        # Load argument 1 into R0
        ldr r0, [fp, #-8]

        # Execute syscall
        swi #0

        # Store result from R0
        str r0, [fp, #-12]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_2" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Linux ARM32 syscall with 2 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into R7
        ldr r7, [fp, #-4]

        # Load arguments 1-2 into R0-R1
        ldr r0, [fp, #-8]
        ldr r1, [fp, #-12]

        # Execute syscall
        swi #0

        # Store result from R0
        str r0, [fp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_3" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Linux ARM32 syscall with 3 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into R7
        ldr r7, [fp, #-4]

        # Load arguments 1-3 into R0-R2
        ldr r0, [fp, #-8]
        ldr r1, [fp, #-12]
        ldr r2, [fp, #-16]

        # Execute syscall
        swi #0

        # Store result from R0
        str r0, [fp, #-20]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_4" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Linux ARM32 syscall with 4 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into R7
        ldr r7, [fp, #-4]

        # Load arguments 1-4 into R0-R3
        ldr r0, [fp, #-8]
        ldr r1, [fp, #-12]
        ldr r2, [fp, #-16]
        ldr r3, [fp, #-20]

        # Execute syscall
        swi #0

        # Store result from R0
        str r0, [fp, #-24]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_5" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Linux ARM32 syscall with 5 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into R7
        ldr r7, [fp, #-4]

        # Load arguments 1-5 into R0-R4
        ldr r0, [fp, #-8]
        ldr r1, [fp, #-12]
        ldr r2, [fp, #-16]
        ldr r3, [fp, #-20]
        ldr r4, [fp, #-24]

        # Execute syscall
        swi #0

        # Store result from R0
        str r0, [fp, #-28]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_6" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Linux ARM32 syscall with 6 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into R7
        ldr r7, [fp, #-4]

        # Load arguments 1-6 into R0-R5
        ldr r0, [fp, #-8]
        ldr r1, [fp, #-12]
        ldr r2, [fp, #-16]
        ldr r3, [fp, #-20]
        ldr r4, [fp, #-24]
        ldr r5, [fp, #-28]

        # Execute syscall
        swi #0

        # Store result from R0
        str r0, [fp, #-32]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER-NAMED SYSCALL WRAPPERS (syscall_<name> bare form)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes 10 `syscall_<name>` bare-name
procs (syscall_read, syscall_write, syscall_open, syscall_close,
syscall_exit, syscall_brk, syscall_mmap, syscall_munmap, syscall_fstat,
syscall_lseek). Each platform module must export the same names so the
dispatcher's bare-name routing can resolve to platform-correct ABI
behaviour. On Linux ARM32 (OABI/EABI), each wrapper routes through the
correct syscall_N generic dispatcher with the matching SYS_* number.

These are NOT duplicates of the lower-section `read`/`write`/`open`/...
wrappers: those use POSIX-style short names for compatibility with the
v0.0.7.5-era Runa standard library; the `syscall_<name>` forms are what
the platform-dispatch infrastructure expects per the P2-B design's
"Per-platform syscall inventory" section.

Source for syscall numbers: Linux kernel
`arch/arm/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h` legacy OABI table (numbers stable
since kernel 2.6; identical on EABI compat).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper computes the syscall number via the matching SYS_* accessor
(itself a constant return on linux_arm32) and forwards arguments to the
`syscall_N` generic dispatcher matching the arity. The generic dispatcher
loads R7 with the syscall number and R0-R5 with arguments, then issues
`swi #0` (equivalent to `svc #0` on EABI) and returns R0. Negative R0
values are Linux-ABI errno indications which the wrapper propagates
unchanged to the caller.

Argument-passing convention:
- syscall_read(fd, buf, count) → SYS_READ(3) via syscall_3
- syscall_write(fd, buf, count) → SYS_WRITE(4) via syscall_3
- syscall_open(path, flags, mode) → SYS_OPEN(5) via syscall_3
- syscall_close(fd) → SYS_CLOSE(6) via syscall_1
- syscall_exit(status) → SYS_EXIT(1) via syscall_1
- syscall_brk(addr) → SYS_BRK(45) via syscall_1
- syscall_mmap(addr, len, prot, flags, fd, offset) → SYS_MMAP(192) via syscall_6 (mmap2 entry)
- syscall_munmap(addr, len) → SYS_MUNMAP(91) via syscall_2
- syscall_fstat(fd, statbuf) → SYS_FSTAT(108) via syscall_2
- syscall_lseek(fd, offset, whence) → SYS_LSEEK(19) via syscall_3

Note on mmap: the OABI/EABI ARM32 entry numbered 192 is the kernel's
`mmap2` (page-offset variant). The dispatcher API treats the 6th argument
as a byte offset on architectures with full mmap; on linux_arm32 the
caller is responsible for page-aligning offset and passing it as a
page-shifted value if compatibility with mmap2 is required. The wrapper
forwards the offset verbatim to match the cross-platform syscall_mmap
contract; callers using byte offsets get -EINVAL from the kernel for
non-page-aligned values, which is the correct ARM32-native behaviour.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Each wrapper compiles down to: load constant syscall number, marshal
arguments through stack frame to R0-R5/R7, issue `swi #0`. Total cost
is dominated by the kernel-mode trap, not the wrapper's Runa-level
indirection. The wrapper itself adds 2-3 instructions of glue beyond
the generic syscall_N body. Do not introduce caching or memoisation;
syscalls are not pure functions and the kernel cost dominates.

For hot-path syscall sites (e.g. read/write in tight I/O loops), prefer
calling the generic `syscall_3` directly with the SYS_* constant inlined,
avoiding the intermediate wrapper. The wrapper exists for dispatcher
contract compliance, not as a recommended fast-path entry.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
File-descriptor and pointer arguments are passed verbatim to the kernel.
The wrapper performs no validation; the kernel enforces all access
controls (UID/GID, capabilities, mount-namespace restrictions, SELinux/
AppArmor policy, seccomp filters). Callers must NOT use these wrappers
to issue syscalls on behalf of an untrusted source without seccomp-bpf
filtering at the process level.

In particular:
- syscall_open: untrusted `path` strings can traverse the filesystem
  subject only to DAC and mount-namespace policy; sandboxed callers
  must impose a chroot or pivot_root before invoking.
- syscall_mmap with PROT_EXEC: writable+executable mappings are a
  W^X violation; callers should request PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE then
  mprotect-up to PROT_EXEC after content is written.
- syscall_exit: terminates the calling thread on EABI ARM32 (kernel
  calls do_exit, not exit_group); to terminate the whole process use
  SYS_EXIT_GROUP via syscall_1 directly.

Errno propagation: kernel returns -errno in R0 for failure. The wrapper
returns this verbatim; positive values are syscall results (e.g. byte
counts, file descriptors, addresses). Caller MUST check sign of return
value before treating it as a syscall result.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read from file descriptor; routes through SYS_READ (3) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_READ()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write to file descriptor; routes through SYS_WRITE (4) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_WRITE()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Open file; routes through SYS_OPEN (5) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_OPEN()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_3(syscall_num, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Close file descriptor; routes through SYS_CLOSE (6) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Terminate calling thread; routes through SYS_EXIT (1) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Note: Does not return on success; the Return statement is unreachable but
    Note: required to satisfy the dispatcher's Integer-return contract
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_EXIT()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Adjust program break; routes through SYS_BRK (45) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Note: addr=0 queries current break; non-zero requests new break address
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_BRK()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map memory; routes through SYS_MMAP (192 = mmap2) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Note: ARM32 has no legacy mmap entry; 192 is the page-offset mmap2
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_MMAP()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unmap memory; routes through SYS_MUNMAP (91) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file status by fd; routes through SYS_FSTAT (108) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Note: statbuf points to a 32-bit `struct stat` (88 bytes on ARM32 OABI)
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "linux_arm32_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reposition file offset; routes through SYS_LSEEK (19) on linux_arm32 OABI
    Note: For 64-bit offsets use SYS__LLSEEK (140) directly; this wrapper is
    Note: limited to 32-bit offsets per the OABI lseek(2) signature
    Let syscall_num be linux_arm32_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return linux_arm32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

